WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.570 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt;Jeffrey Freburg: Hi, everyone.

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:05.680
Welcome.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:06.680
[crowd chatter]

00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:09.630
So, it's a real pleasure of mine to introduce
our guest today, Chef Jacques Pepin.

00:00:09.630 --> 00:00:13.440
He actually taught me how to cook when I was
a little kid, so it's really a treat for me

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:14.440
to talk to you today.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:15.440
So, welcome to Google.

00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:16.980
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Thank you.

00:00:16.980 --> 00:00:18.119
[applause]

00:00:18.119 --> 00:00:23.269
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, you're here to talk about
your new book, and--.

00:00:23.269 --> 00:00:25.349
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: That's what I'm here for.

00:00:25.349 --> 00:00:26.349
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yes.

00:00:26.349 --> 00:00:27.349
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: OK.

00:00:27.349 --> 00:00:28.349
Good.

00:00:28.349 --> 00:00:29.349
[laughter]

00:00:29.349 --> 00:00:30.880
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, well, hopefully we can
get you a little lunch, too, on top of that.

00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:31.880
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: All right.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:33.270
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: But really love the book.

00:00:33.270 --> 00:00:39.670
It seems like a great recipe bank, but one
thing that I really liked about it was the

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:41.810
discs that you included, with all techniques.

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:42.810
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yes.

00:00:42.810 --> 00:00:44.449
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, you wanna talk about that
a little bit?

00:00:44.449 --> 00:00:45.719
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yes.

00:00:45.719 --> 00:00:48.879
Probably I would agree with you.

00:00:48.879 --> 00:00:56.430
The DVD that I have in there, three hours
of technique, ran from tightening your apron

00:00:56.430 --> 00:01:01.609
to sharpening a knife to boning out a chicken,
making an omelet, doing a caramel cage.

00:01:01.609 --> 00:01:05.050
All of those are very visual and very difficult
to explain in word.

00:01:05.050 --> 00:01:09.900
It take page and page for me to tell you how
to do a cornet with a piece of wax paper.

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:12.110
You know, to do decoration.

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:17.280
Fold it in the right angle, cross it in the
center of the hypotenuse, your [inaudible

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:18.930
] your right hand.

00:01:18.930 --> 00:01:20.549
Fold it.

00:01:20.549 --> 00:01:21.650
You see it done.

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:22.650
Yeah.

00:01:22.650 --> 00:01:26.060
You see it done and it's that's the beauty
of it.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:29.940
And I am Dean of Study at the French Culinary
Institute in New York City.

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:36.130
And I teach at BU, Boston University, for
about 31 years.

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:37.939
Something like that.

00:01:37.939 --> 00:01:42.369
I live in Connecticut, as you see by my Yankee
drawl.

00:01:42.369 --> 00:01:43.670
[laughter]

00:01:43.670 --> 00:01:47.899
So, and in those school, I mean, this is the
technique that we teach.

00:01:47.899 --> 00:01:51.860
Fifty, forty-five thousand dollars at the
French Culinary Institute for the program.

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:54.840
But that's basically it, you know?

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:57.710
And the technique for me are very important.

00:01:57.710 --> 00:02:02.700
It's a question of repeat, repeat, repeat,
repeat, so that it becomes so much part of

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:06.380
yourself that now you can afford to forget
it.

00:02:06.380 --> 00:02:13.050
Now, I can think in term of color or texture
stuff and my hands are just moving.

00:02:13.050 --> 00:02:16.560
And certainly, for anyone who work in the--.

00:02:16.560 --> 00:02:18.720
Can you hear me OK?

00:02:18.720 --> 00:02:19.720
Yeah.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:24.110
Anyone who work with his hand, whether you
are a cabinet maker, whether you are a surgeon

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:29.250
for that matter, a sculptor, a painter and
all that, you first have to become a craftsman

00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:30.940
in my book.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:35.830
And if you happen to have talent, then the
craftmanship in your hand enable you to take

00:02:35.830 --> 00:02:38.180
that talent somewhere and do something with
it.

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:42.310
So, if you're a good craftsman, you can run
a restaurant.

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:47.000
I knew a fair amount of chef who run restaurant,
but they are relatively lousy cook.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.090
But they are a good craftsman, so they run
the place fine.

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:55.700
Someone has a lot of talent and you can take
that--if you are Thomas Keller or someone

00:02:55.700 --> 00:03:01.580
like this and you can really bring it to extraordinary
food, or to great food maybe.

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:05.980
And if you put a bit of love into it, then
it make it to extraordinary food and so.

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:10.350
So, I am very happy with that DVD.

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:17.190
I do that, I mean, I've been teaching or doing
show on television here, actually at KQED

00:03:17.190 --> 00:03:18.610
for the last 25 years.

00:03:18.610 --> 00:03:22.450
I've done 12 series of 26 show here in the
last.

00:03:22.450 --> 00:03:25.150
And out of that book, there is a series now,
which is here.

00:03:25.150 --> 00:03:28.820
I think it's Saturday morning, my show here
at KQED.

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:31.960
So, we did 26 show usually series.

00:03:31.960 --> 00:03:35.660
Twenty-six show for some reason on PBS.

00:03:35.660 --> 00:03:39.630
And I have four, five recipe in each of those
series.

00:03:39.630 --> 00:03:41.770
I have my daughter on it and my granddaughter.

00:03:41.770 --> 00:03:43.960
I have my friend Jean-Claude.

00:03:43.960 --> 00:03:46.510
So, this is part of the book as well.

00:03:46.510 --> 00:03:49.360
And it's always better to see it done than
just to read it.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.650
But the recipes themselves, I didn't even
want to do that book.

00:03:53.650 --> 00:03:58.960
This is, I think, number 27, my books which
I have done many book.

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:06.190
And that book a kind of recap of recipe book
which were out of print that we start looking

00:04:06.190 --> 00:04:07.190
at again.

00:04:07.190 --> 00:04:12.370
So, I started doing about 25 hundred recipe
there, a lot where we don't have.

00:04:12.370 --> 00:04:13.780
I look at salmon.

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:15.120
I see three or four salmon.

00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:16.150
They have tomato in it.

00:04:16.150 --> 00:04:18.200
So, I eliminate and so forth.

00:04:18.200 --> 00:04:22.790
And the point is, well, either to leave it
the way it was--.

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:26.710
I think the New York Times did a big book
last year, the "New York Times Cookbook,"

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:28.650
the last 30, 40 years.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:32.810
And they left the recipe the way they were
at that time.

00:04:32.810 --> 00:04:34.110
And it was just to show people.

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:38.820
So, it was either this for me or change them
to make them usable and more in the style

00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:39.830
of what we do today.

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:42.280
And I choose the second option.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:44.640
And it end up being more work than doing a
book.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:49.940
[laughs] So, from scratch, we don't cook the
vegetable in the same amount of time.

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:51.870
Fish also--amount of cooking.

00:04:51.870 --> 00:04:55.980
The amount of fat that we put in it, the type
of fatâ€”from butter to cream to olive oil

00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:57.810
to--all change a great deal.

00:04:57.810 --> 00:04:59.060
There are a fair amount of changes.

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:04.230
But anyway, so it came out in the fall last
year.

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:06.170
And we did that series on television.

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:07.720
It started.

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:13.640
And I was supposed to be here last fall to
publish, to do a book tour, which I did part

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:14.640
of it.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:20.300
And all of a sudden, I had to have a hip replacement,
so I was stuck for a little while.

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:22.150
The beauty of getting old, you know?

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.740
And now I'm back.

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:24.740
So.

00:05:24.740 --> 00:05:25.740
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yeah.

00:05:25.740 --> 00:05:30.210
And so, I watched your DVD and one thing that
I found very interesting is that you mentioned

00:05:30.210 --> 00:05:33.860
that like, through your career, you changed
your technique.

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:37.670
Do you wanna talk about that and how you changed
and what you did?

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:40.430
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Well, actually I don't know.

00:05:40.430 --> 00:05:43.030
I think I said I don't change my technique.

00:05:43.030 --> 00:05:44.380
Can that, the--.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:45.380
Yeah.

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:51.430
A little bit, but I have a book called "La
Technique," an illustrated manual of cooking

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:52.430
technique.

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:56.210
Very large book, which have three thousand
picture, black and white.

00:05:56.210 --> 00:06:03.100
[clears throat] I did that book in '76, I
believe, the book called "La Technique," and

00:06:03.100 --> 00:06:07.180
a follow-up called "La Methode," who are looking
for a similar name.

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:10.060
And eventually, those two book got together,
which is that large book.

00:06:10.060 --> 00:06:18.290
Well, that book got a prize two years ago
in Europe for whatever and I won, at the IACP--International

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:22.960
Association Culinary Professional--was in
New York two weeks ago, as one of the greatest

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.600
book of well, the last half-Century or whatever.

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:30.640
And not saying that to brag, but maybe a little
bit, but--

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:31.640
[laughter]

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:36.010
the point is that book is still in print because
the technique are the same--the way you sharpen

00:06:36.010 --> 00:06:39.110
a knife, the way you beat an egg white, the
way you do an omelet.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:41.420
All of that have never changed.

00:06:41.420 --> 00:06:46.330
I mean, my recipe are quite different than
they would have been 25, 30 years ago, but

00:06:46.330 --> 00:06:48.050
the technique themself are the same.

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:52.950
And that's why you try to teach technique
in a professional school.

00:06:52.950 --> 00:06:54.690
That is, teaching you how to cook.

00:06:54.690 --> 00:06:59.520
And then, after you take it and you do something
else with it.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:02.790
I mean, as a young chef, it's not too complicated.

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:04.910
All you have say is, "Yes, Chef."

00:07:04.910 --> 00:07:06.440
Chef never asks your opinion.

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.880
So, you work with someone for a year, year
and a half.

00:07:09.880 --> 00:07:13.320
Someone like Thomas Keller at Bouchon, if
you have the chance to.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:19.210
And you're idea there, really, is to try to
visualize the food through his eyes, through

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:23.790
his sense of aesthetic, and through his talent
because that's why you work there--to work

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:24.790
with someone like that.

00:07:24.790 --> 00:07:26.580
So, you absorb as much as you can.

00:07:26.580 --> 00:07:31.210
And you move to that area of New York and
you do the same thing for another two years.

00:07:31.210 --> 00:07:35.320
Then, you move to Jean-Georges or whatever
and do the same thing for another two years.

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:40.660
And after five, six year, that young chef
had absorbed an enormous amount of material

00:07:40.660 --> 00:07:41.850
just saying, "Yes, Chef."

00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:47.669
At that time, you kind of--excuse the pun--but
you can regurgitate it.

00:07:47.669 --> 00:07:51.990
But now, you filter it through your sense
of aesthetic, your sense of taste.

00:07:51.990 --> 00:07:55.710
And now, you start doing your food, but not
before that really.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:56.910
It does take time.

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:58.890
What am I talking about anyway?

00:07:58.890 --> 00:07:59.890
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Oh, nothing.

00:07:59.890 --> 00:08:00.890
[laughter]

00:08:00.890 --> 00:08:01.890
That was great.

00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:03.490
So, I heard a really interesting fact.

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:09.200
At the time you were offered the job with
the Kennedy's to be the Chef at the White

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:11.760
House and you turned it down to work for Howard
Johnsons.

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:14.300
I'd like to hear more about that.

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:17.430
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Not a big deal.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:18.430
[laughter]

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:19.430
It's not really.

00:08:19.430 --> 00:08:23.380
I mean, I had been the chef in France from
'56 to '59 to three Presidents.

00:08:23.380 --> 00:08:26.330
I finished with de Gaulle in '59.

00:08:26.330 --> 00:08:28.370
So, I came to this country.

00:08:28.370 --> 00:08:29.740
I work at Le Pavillon in New York.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.260
I was going to stay here two years in New
York.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:39.400
Most people come to America to get a better
life for economic reason, religious reason,

00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:41.270
political reason, too.

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:43.770
It wasn't my case.

00:08:43.770 --> 00:08:48.980
I work at Le Pavillon, which was considered
maybe the greatest restaurant, French restaurant,

00:08:48.980 --> 00:08:51.550
in America at that time.

00:08:51.550 --> 00:08:59.990
And I worked there and Howard Johnson was
one of our customer, Howard D. Johnson, the

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:01.440
one who created the company.

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:11.060
But in the Spring of 1961, Kennedy were very
regular at the house, start to planning for

00:09:11.060 --> 00:09:12.860
the White House, so they called me.

00:09:12.860 --> 00:09:14.600
At that time, it was very casual.

00:09:14.600 --> 00:09:20.110
I mean, did they call the owner of La Caravelle,
the restaurant which called Roger, the chef.

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:21.160
Roger called me.

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:23.260
I said, "I don't think so."

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:30.240
Pierre Franey was at the Le Pavillon, was
leaving to go to Howard Johnson and he said,

00:09:30.240 --> 00:09:31.660
"Come with me," and so forth.

00:09:31.660 --> 00:09:39.320
So, he had no idea, to be truthful, of the
inkling of the possibility of publicity from

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:41.870
the White House and all that because he did
not exist.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:46.450
So, you have to realize that 30 years ago,
I would never have been sitting here.

00:09:46.450 --> 00:09:51.080
The chef at the bottom of the social scale
and when I was in Paris, when I worked with

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:55.360
the French President, I served people like
Eisenhower, Nehru, Tito, Maximilan--those

00:09:55.360 --> 00:09:59.510
that were Head of State at the time.

00:09:59.510 --> 00:10:04.529
No one ever would come to the kitchen, not
even a thank you or whatever.

00:10:04.529 --> 00:10:06.960
You'd never even have a thank you or anyone
thanks.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:09.280
Someone comes to the kitchen because something
was wrong.

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:10.910
And then you get it.

00:10:10.910 --> 00:10:12.490
But otherwise, never, you never.

00:10:12.490 --> 00:10:13.730
So, that was the way it was.

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:14.860
I mean, I'm not complaining.

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:16.750
It was the way it was for everybody.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:24.060
So, when I was asked to go to the White House,
I had no idea of the possibility of publicity.

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:28.660
I'd never been in a newspaper, in a magazine,
television barely existed.

00:10:28.660 --> 00:10:29.740
So, that was--.

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:33.649
Any good mother would have wanted her child
to marry a doctor, a lawyer, an architect,

00:10:33.649 --> 00:10:36.190
but certainly not a cook, you know?

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:37.190
[laughter]

00:10:37.190 --> 00:10:38.190
Now, we are genius.

00:10:38.190 --> 00:10:40.320
So, I don't know what happened.

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:41.320
[laughter]

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:47.710
In any case, to validate my choice, this is
I did that certainly because of that.

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:48.760
I didn't realize.

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:50.710
But it was very good.

00:10:50.710 --> 00:10:54.320
I worked ten years Director of Research for
Howard Johnson.

00:10:54.320 --> 00:11:01.190
I did work like specific gravity and coliform
and that area stuff.

00:11:01.190 --> 00:11:03.180
I learned the American eating habit.

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:07.050
I worked in a totally American environment.

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:10.120
So, it was very good for me.

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:12.890
I opened the World Trade Center in 1973, I
believe.

00:11:12.890 --> 00:11:14.790
Yeah, '73.

00:11:14.790 --> 00:11:19.960
I opened a restaurant first when I left Howard
Johnson on 5th Avenue in New York called La

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:20.960
Potagerie.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:25.490
It was a place with a very high volume to
some group of investor wanted to do that,

00:11:25.490 --> 00:11:28.230
so I created the concept, the name, and I
did thing.

00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:31.800
Then I opened the World Trade Center in 1974.

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:35.410
I did a commissary on the list for the two
tower.

00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:39.870
And we had 26 restaurants on the main course.

00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:43.130
And that, in addition, Window of the World,
Skyline on 44th Street and so forth.

00:11:43.130 --> 00:11:53.959
I have to say that the commissary that I had
under Tower One was blown out in 1993 by a

00:11:53.959 --> 00:11:56.990
guy who brought the truck there with bomb
in it, you know?

00:11:56.990 --> 00:11:57.990
A terrorist.

00:11:57.990 --> 00:11:59.540
And they blew out that part of the building,
the terrorists.

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:03.040
And then after, of course, they blew the whole
things.

00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:07.399
After that, I work, I was a consultant for
the Russian Tea Room in New York, too.

00:12:07.399 --> 00:12:12.360
I am staying only on those job because I could
never have been able to do the commissary

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:19.750
at the World Trade Center, or that soup place,
or the Russian Tea Room, if I hadn't had the

00:12:19.750 --> 00:12:21.529
training of Howard Johnson that I had.

00:12:21.529 --> 00:12:25.140
As a chef, I didn't know anything about production,
stuff like this.

00:12:25.140 --> 00:12:26.354
So, Howard Johnson was very good to me--

00:12:26.354 --> 00:12:27.354
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Great.

00:12:27.354 --> 00:12:28.354
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: in that way.

00:12:28.354 --> 00:12:31.950
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what are some of your
fondest food memories?

00:12:31.950 --> 00:12:38.150
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Fondest food memories are
always sitting down with my wife or my mother

00:12:38.150 --> 00:12:39.870
or my kid or friend.

00:12:39.870 --> 00:12:42.040
Friend is always the fondest.

00:12:42.040 --> 00:12:45.010
I mean, food itself is nothing in itself.

00:12:45.010 --> 00:12:49.620
The sharing of the food and on the table and
all that is what makes it.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:56.790
I mean, this is maybe the most civilized way
of having a conversation--around food--and

00:12:56.790 --> 00:12:57.790
discuss it.

00:12:57.790 --> 00:12:58.800
So, that's important.

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:05.000
In my family, it's, of course, with bread
and wine there is always bread and wine on

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.810
the table [laughs] so we can see a meal.

00:13:07.810 --> 00:13:10.690
Without a basket of bread and a bottle of
wine.

00:13:10.690 --> 00:13:14.000
And I've been married 45, almost 46 years.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:19.570
And I don't remember one day that my wife
and I didn't sit down for dinner--don't have

00:13:19.570 --> 00:13:21.510
time really for lunch.

00:13:21.510 --> 00:13:26.950
We sit a little bit for lunch, but having
dinner and drinking wine, often two bottles

00:13:26.950 --> 00:13:28.029
of wine,

00:13:28.029 --> 00:13:29.029
[laughter]

00:13:29.029 --> 00:13:33.173
but the point is if I start cooking at four
o'clock in the afternoon, I happen to have

00:13:33.173 --> 00:13:37.610
a bottle of wine--white wine--and then, by
the time we sit down to eat at seven, eight

00:13:37.610 --> 00:13:38.610
o'clock, it's gone.

00:13:38.610 --> 00:13:40.730
So, we open a bottle of red wine.

00:13:40.730 --> 00:13:41.730
[laughter]

00:13:41.730 --> 00:13:45.610
So, now when I go see my doctor, he say "How
much wine do you drink?"

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:49.570
I've decided to only buy my wine in magnum
now--

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:50.570
[laughter]

00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:56.029
because I say, "One bottle a day."

00:13:56.029 --> 00:13:57.029
Then, I avoid problem.

00:13:57.029 --> 00:13:58.029
[laughter]

00:13:58.029 --> 00:14:00.900
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, you mentioned that you
were cooking with your daughter and your granddaughter.

00:14:00.900 --> 00:14:02.820
Are they good cooks as well?

00:14:02.820 --> 00:14:05.430
Has that been a good bonding experience for
you?

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:08.890
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Well, my wife is a good cook.

00:14:08.890 --> 00:14:12.950
My wife was born in New York City from a Puerto
Rican mother and a Cuban father, so she's

00:14:12.950 --> 00:14:14.670
a real New Yorker.

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:20.160
That's why that book, often I maybe looked
at on the quintessential French chef, you

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:24.870
get to page--I don't know--32 and you have
black bean soup with banana and cilantro on

00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:26.820
top, which is really Cuban.

00:14:26.820 --> 00:14:27.830
Next, you have ceviche.

00:14:27.830 --> 00:14:30.350
Next, you have whatever.

00:14:30.350 --> 00:14:35.100
That represent the last 50 years in my life
for me in America.

00:14:35.100 --> 00:14:39.740
So, it's a very American cookbook in that
sense.

00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:46.459
I do have some true French technique and French
recipe, but in a sense, I don't try to be

00:14:46.459 --> 00:14:48.220
French.

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:50.660
And by the same token, I don't try not to
be French.

00:14:50.660 --> 00:14:53.290
I don't really think about it in those terms.

00:14:53.290 --> 00:14:54.940
I cook whatever is around.

00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:57.820
And I have a place in Mexico.

00:14:57.820 --> 00:14:58.820
Just came back ten weeks.

00:14:58.820 --> 00:15:04.480
So, I go there, buy a bandera, look at a paper
and can start cooking with that.

00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:07.950
So, that make its way into recipe.

00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:12.960
And the series that I did before, I did two
series on PBS prior to this one.

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:18.760
I've done 12 here, but two series, the last
two, were called "Fast Food My Way."

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:25.250
And those were, each one of them has a little
book, and those are very easy recipe to follow

00:15:25.250 --> 00:15:26.250
through.

00:15:26.250 --> 00:15:29.450
Maybe the best, maybe the recipe that people
use maybe the most.

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:36.930
What I did there in those book, when you are
in a professional kitchen, you have the prep

00:15:36.930 --> 00:15:38.630
cook who came in the morning.

00:15:38.630 --> 00:15:40.950
"La maison plas," we call it in French.

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:46.690
So, the prep cook bone out the chicken, bone
out the fish, slice the mushroom, shell the

00:15:46.690 --> 00:15:48.790
shallot, wash the spinach, they do all that
stuff.

00:15:48.790 --> 00:15:51.620
Shove the tomato and all that, so you have
everything ready.

00:15:51.620 --> 00:15:55.410
I get to the stove, everything is fresh ready.

00:15:55.410 --> 00:15:56.550
Someone order filet of sole.

00:15:56.550 --> 00:15:58.120
I grab the filet of sole ready.

00:15:58.120 --> 00:16:03.750
I put some shallots on top, a bit of sliced
mushroom, dash of white wine, bit of olive

00:16:03.750 --> 00:16:05.640
oil, bring it to a boil, finish it up.

00:16:05.640 --> 00:16:08.550
I do it in three, four minutes, five minutes.

00:16:08.550 --> 00:16:09.550
Why?

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:10.550
Because everything is ready.

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:13.339
So, that what the premise is in those book.

00:16:13.339 --> 00:16:15.670
I use the supermarket as a prep cook.

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:18.860
I can go there, buy two breast of boneless,
skinless chicken.

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:20.860
I use a no-stick pan.

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:24.820
I have pre-wash spinach, pre-sliced mushroom,
whatever I can buy at the market.

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:28.250
And with minimum amount of effort, fresh food,
I can do a menu.

00:16:28.250 --> 00:16:31.860
In fact, when we did that, those show are
half an hour.

00:16:31.860 --> 00:16:33.300
I did three dish.

00:16:33.300 --> 00:16:34.670
I never use the back kitchen.

00:16:34.670 --> 00:16:40.570
I did those three dish, or four dish sometime,
in the 30 minutes that I was on television.

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:42.000
So, it's a nice way of cooking, too.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.900
A bit different from that, you know?

00:16:44.900 --> 00:16:52.440
And certainly, at the [inaudible] if you want
of my book on technique, where if I don't

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:54.980
show you how to prep the chicken, and goose,
too.

00:16:54.980 --> 00:16:56.240
I used to.

00:16:56.240 --> 00:17:01.920
Skin the rabbit and then cut it and eviscerate
it and so forth, that's cooking from the beginning.

00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:04.490
It's another way of doing it, you know?

00:17:04.490 --> 00:17:07.250
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what was the last meal
that you made?

00:17:07.250 --> 00:17:09.669
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Last meal that I made.

00:17:09.669 --> 00:17:10.669
OK.

00:17:10.669 --> 00:17:13.659
When did I leave home?

00:17:13.659 --> 00:17:19.760
I was in Pebble Beach Thursday, Friday, Saturday
for the Food and Wine Festival.

00:17:19.760 --> 00:17:22.730
Then, I was in Phoenix on the PBS station.

00:17:22.730 --> 00:17:25.769
I did like, five show and other things.

00:17:25.769 --> 00:17:27.929
And I came here on Monday.

00:17:27.929 --> 00:17:31.040
So, Friday.

00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:33.610
Wednesday night we went out for dinner.

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:34.879
[laughter]

00:17:34.879 --> 00:17:38.489
I think Tuesday, the Tuesday before I did
a chicken.

00:17:38.489 --> 00:17:39.489
Oh, no.

00:17:39.489 --> 00:17:41.460
The last time I cooked was in Pebble Beach.

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:42.590
I did a chicken in vinegar.

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:45.869
They are the most special with my daughter,
which I have in there.

00:17:45.869 --> 00:17:48.609
Chicken in vinegar, which I thought was really
good.

00:17:48.609 --> 00:17:49.609
[Jeff Freburg laughs]

00:17:49.609 --> 00:17:51.350
I mean, I haven't done that in 25 years.

00:17:51.350 --> 00:17:52.789
I didn't even remember it.

00:17:52.789 --> 00:17:53.789
I say, "Wow.

00:17:53.789 --> 00:17:54.789
That's good."

00:17:54.789 --> 00:17:55.789
[laughter]

00:17:55.789 --> 00:18:00.759
And I did a mashed potato, turnips, turnips
and potato, mashed potato with garlic in it,

00:18:00.759 --> 00:18:01.929
and some apple fritter.

00:18:01.929 --> 00:18:02.929
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: OK.

00:18:02.929 --> 00:18:05.010
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: So, that's what I did.

00:18:05.010 --> 00:18:06.010
Yeah.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:08.659
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what are some of the things
that you really like to cook?

00:18:08.659 --> 00:18:10.390
What are some of your favorite ingredients?

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:12.850
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: The market, you know?

00:18:12.850 --> 00:18:15.659
The market and the season for me, that will
define.

00:18:15.659 --> 00:18:19.850
But I mean, certainly, I could be on an island
if there is chicken and eggs.

00:18:19.850 --> 00:18:24.039
Eggs, for me, I love eggs.

00:18:24.039 --> 00:18:27.330
But people say, "What's the best thing you
can put in your mouth?"

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:32.210
Well, if I have the greatest possible bread
that I can take and the greatest possible

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:36.059
butter, very hard to beat bread and butter,
I tell you.

00:18:36.059 --> 00:18:37.059
[laughter]

00:18:37.059 --> 00:18:40.309
And that being said, there is many other thing
you cook, but--.

00:18:40.309 --> 00:18:43.879
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what are some of your
favorite restaurants in San Francisco?

00:18:43.879 --> 00:18:46.380
And where are you going to be eating while
you're here?

00:18:46.380 --> 00:18:49.220
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: That's a leading question,
right?

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:50.220
[laughter]

00:18:50.220 --> 00:18:54.230
But certainly, to paraphrase James Beard,
I think who said the best restaurant is where

00:18:54.230 --> 00:18:56.859
they know you, and it's true in many ways.

00:18:56.859 --> 00:18:59.210
I'll go see my friend [inaudible]--

00:18:59.210 --> 00:19:01.169
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yeah.

00:19:01.169 --> 00:19:03.140
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: too.

00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:06.649
I stay at the, I used to love Ter Posterie.

00:19:06.649 --> 00:19:09.740
I stay at the Prescott Hotel now.

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:11.039
Now, it's closed, too.

00:19:11.039 --> 00:19:14.090
But there is so many other restaurant that
I go to here.

00:19:14.090 --> 00:19:18.950
I mean, tonight I'm going to be.

00:19:18.950 --> 00:19:19.950
Tonight?

00:19:19.950 --> 00:19:20.950
Yes.

00:19:20.950 --> 00:19:21.950
Yeah.

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:22.950
City, City Center.

00:19:22.950 --> 00:19:23.950
Whatever there is that.

00:19:23.950 --> 00:19:27.840
And I'm being carried by Daniel Patterson,
from Coi, you know?

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:33.539
And while La Folie, this is a great restaurant.

00:19:33.539 --> 00:19:35.639
I mean, two star in the Michelin.

00:19:35.639 --> 00:19:37.299
It's extraordinary.

00:19:37.299 --> 00:19:43.169
With that being said, if I'm here for a while,
when I come and we film, we end up in Chinatown

00:19:43.169 --> 00:19:44.169
a fair amount of time.

00:19:44.169 --> 00:19:47.220
I love Chinese food and other type of Oriental
food.

00:19:47.220 --> 00:19:51.451
As well as when you go down Post, you turn
underneath that alley.

00:19:51.451 --> 00:19:52.451
I forget.

00:19:52.451 --> 00:19:53.451
Something Alley and there is--.

