&gt;&gt;male #1: Belden?

00:19:54.451 --> 00:19:55.451
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Ah?

00:19:55.451 --> 00:19:56.451
&gt;&gt;male #1: Belden, maybe?

00:19:56.451 --> 00:19:57.750
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: There is a Spanish restaurant
there.

00:19:57.750 --> 00:19:58.929
There's a French restaurant.

00:19:58.929 --> 00:20:00.590
Three or four, five little restaurant.

00:20:00.590 --> 00:20:02.710
Really good, especially the Spanish one.

00:20:02.710 --> 00:20:03.710
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: OK.

00:20:03.710 --> 00:20:05.549
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: I forget the name of it,
though.

00:20:05.549 --> 00:20:06.549
But--.

00:20:06.549 --> 00:20:07.549
&gt;&gt;male #1: Belden.

00:20:07.549 --> 00:20:08.549
B-E-L-D-E-N.

00:20:08.549 --> 00:20:09.549
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: B-E-A-L?

00:20:09.549 --> 00:20:10.549
&gt;&gt;male #1: B-E-L.

00:20:10.549 --> 00:20:11.549
Belden.

00:20:11.549 --> 00:20:12.549
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Oh, yeah.

00:20:12.549 --> 00:20:13.549
I think so.

00:20:13.549 --> 00:20:14.549
Yes.

00:20:14.549 --> 00:20:15.549
Right.

00:20:15.549 --> 00:20:16.549
Yeah.

00:20:16.549 --> 00:20:17.549
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, when people found out
I was gonna talk to you today, everyone wanted

00:20:17.549 --> 00:20:18.549
me to ask you about Julia.

00:20:18.549 --> 00:20:19.549
So, do you care to talk about that?

00:20:19.549 --> 00:20:20.549
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: No.

00:20:20.549 --> 00:20:24.960
I mean, actually, I just did a tribute to
her yesterday for KQED.

00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:27.169
And I had another one at the IACP here.

00:20:27.169 --> 00:20:29.210
I speak with the tape.

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:33.399
And then, I'm doing one with the WNET in New
York, WGBH in Boston, W--.

00:20:33.399 --> 00:20:38.470
There are gonna be her hundredth birthday,
on the twelve of August.

00:20:38.470 --> 00:20:43.489
So, people are doing a tribute to her.

00:20:43.489 --> 00:20:49.639
I met Julia in 1961, or '60.

00:20:49.639 --> 00:20:51.389
1960.

00:20:51.389 --> 00:20:52.940
Food world was really, really small.

00:20:52.940 --> 00:20:54.269
And I say, "Well,--."

00:20:54.269 --> 00:20:59.720
Craig Claiborne was the food editor of the
New York Time, which many people have forgotten

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:04.309
as one of the most important figure in food
in the last half a century.

00:21:04.309 --> 00:21:06.519
And James Beard.

00:21:06.519 --> 00:21:13.850
And Julia, James Beard, Craig Claiborne, were
very, the trinity of cooking in this country.

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:19.419
When I work at Le Pavillon there in 1959-60,
Craig came to Le Pavillon to do an article

00:21:19.419 --> 00:21:21.529
on Le Pavillon and Pierre.

00:21:21.529 --> 00:21:23.140
And I became friend with him.

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:25.400
He introduced me to Helen McCullough.

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:29.609
Helen McCullough was the food editor of McCall
House Beautiful.

00:21:29.609 --> 00:21:31.289
And she was never married.

00:21:31.289 --> 00:21:34.559
She was an old lady and she took me under
her wing.

00:21:34.559 --> 00:21:36.759
I mean, she was kind of my surrogate mother.

00:21:36.759 --> 00:21:38.259
"Don't wear those stupid socks.

00:21:38.259 --> 00:21:39.279
Don't wear this."

00:21:39.279 --> 00:21:40.279
You know?

00:21:40.279 --> 00:21:41.279
That type of thing.

00:21:41.279 --> 00:21:46.260
And, but she spoke with James Beard on the
telephone, like two hours every day.

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:48.850
So, through her, I knew James Beard a few
weeks later.

00:21:48.850 --> 00:21:51.470
And in the Spring of 1960, Helen told me,
"Here.

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:52.820
I have a manuscript.

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:56.200
I want you to look at that manuscript I received
there."

00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:58.590
I said, "Yes, it's pretty good.

00:21:58.590 --> 00:21:59.590
Very nice.

00:21:59.590 --> 00:22:00.590
Explain."

00:22:00.590 --> 00:22:02.419
So, she said, "Well, the woman is from California.

00:22:02.419 --> 00:22:04.259
She's coming to New York next week.

00:22:04.259 --> 00:22:05.259
Let's cook for her."

00:22:05.259 --> 00:22:07.499
She was a big woman with a terrible voice--

00:22:07.499 --> 00:22:08.499
[laughter]

00:22:08.499 --> 00:22:09.600
but for a cook, that was Julia.

00:22:09.600 --> 00:22:14.659
So, first time I met her, I spoke French with
her.

00:22:14.659 --> 00:22:18.860
Actually, my French was better than my English.

00:22:18.860 --> 00:22:20.539
And that was 1960.

00:22:20.539 --> 00:22:25.019
So, at that point, no one knew her because
television did not exist.

00:22:25.019 --> 00:22:27.679
She didn't do any television.

00:22:27.679 --> 00:22:31.610
And she had never written a book, of course.

00:22:31.610 --> 00:22:35.080
And she never wrote for a magazine, newspaper,
whatever.

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:36.249
So, she wasn't known.

00:22:36.249 --> 00:22:37.369
She just came from France.

00:22:37.369 --> 00:22:40.509
She had been at Le Courdon Bleu for a number
of years.

00:22:40.509 --> 00:22:41.799
So, that's how I met her.

00:22:41.799 --> 00:22:43.779
So, we stay friend.

00:22:43.779 --> 00:22:46.359
And then, she lived in Cambridge.

00:22:46.359 --> 00:22:49.809
So, I teach at BU, as I said, for 31 years
now.

00:22:49.809 --> 00:22:55.570
So, each time I go to BU, I call her for breakfast,
lunch, or dinner and then we started doing

00:22:55.570 --> 00:22:57.759
classes for the student at BU just for fun.

00:22:57.759 --> 00:22:58.759
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Mm-hmm.

00:22:58.759 --> 00:23:01.779
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: And I said, "Well, let's
do a special for PBS on that."

00:23:01.779 --> 00:23:05.490
So, we did "Cooking in Concert," a two-hour
special for PBS.

00:23:05.490 --> 00:23:06.760
We did at BU.

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:10.419
In a couple of years, we did another one.

00:23:10.419 --> 00:23:13.989
And we were giving a lot of class together
and finally, we did a series together.

00:23:13.989 --> 00:23:18.690
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what are some of the things
that you're most proud of looking back on

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:19.690
your career?

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:22.479
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Well, it's to make people
happy.

00:23:22.479 --> 00:23:24.190
That's what cooking is all about.

00:23:24.190 --> 00:23:25.970
It's rewarding.

00:23:25.970 --> 00:23:33.499
In our time of political correctness, we cannot
talk about gender, about size, about color,

00:23:33.499 --> 00:23:40.029
about religion, about anything, so we talk
about food--the only safe thing we can talk

00:23:40.029 --> 00:23:41.029
about.

00:23:41.029 --> 00:23:42.509
So, that's what happened.

00:23:42.509 --> 00:23:44.700
And spending time around the table.

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:51.620
And yesterday, I was on the Michael Krasny
Forum show, which is a very good show.

00:23:51.620 --> 00:23:56.720
It's amazing the amount of people who call
you and say, "You kind of changed my life

00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:57.890
by [inaudible] my father."

00:23:57.890 --> 00:23:58.890
And all that, too.

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:01.990
And I know I had that book, "La Technique,"
like I said.

00:24:01.990 --> 00:24:05.190
And people used to say, "Can you sign that
book for me?

00:24:05.190 --> 00:24:06.190
It's great."

00:24:06.190 --> 00:24:09.350
A number of years went by and they say, "You
know, my mother is crazy about you.

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:10.720
Could you sign that book for her?"

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:14.480
And then now, people say, "You know, my grandmother
really likes you a lot."

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:15.480
[laughter]

00:24:15.480 --> 00:24:16.480
Whoa.

00:24:16.480 --> 00:24:18.190
That book has been there.

00:24:18.190 --> 00:24:23.159
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, what do you think about
the state of cuisine in America and where

00:24:23.159 --> 00:24:25.019
do you think it's gonna be headed towards?

00:24:25.019 --> 00:24:31.039
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Well, this is basically an
impossible question because as I said, my

00:24:31.039 --> 00:24:36.669
book here is probably a very American book
now because the ethnicity in it and the change

00:24:36.669 --> 00:24:37.669
and all that.

00:24:37.669 --> 00:24:45.140
I mean, if you go to France, people still
each French 98, 99 percent of the time.

00:24:45.140 --> 00:24:50.639
There is some Chinese or Italian restaurant,
but basically, the cuisine is this way.

00:24:50.639 --> 00:24:53.090
It's part of your tradition.

00:24:53.090 --> 00:24:54.879
It's kind of visceral and that's how you eat.

00:24:54.879 --> 00:24:55.879
And that the way it is in Italy.

00:24:55.879 --> 00:25:00.860
And that the way it is in Spain or in Portugal
and Germany, for that matter, too.

00:25:00.860 --> 00:25:03.549
But not America.

00:25:03.549 --> 00:25:07.729
People eat Turkish one night and they go to
Chinese one day, to especially in urban center

00:25:07.729 --> 00:25:09.769
like this, the center of the world.

00:25:09.769 --> 00:25:14.929
And this is the reason why someone like me
could come from another country and make it

00:25:14.929 --> 00:25:19.840
to a certain extent, which would be difficult
for--certainly much harder--for Chinese chef

00:25:19.840 --> 00:25:23.519
or Greek chef, to make it in France or in
another country in Europe.

00:25:23.519 --> 00:25:27.539
It's America that that the way it is.

00:25:27.539 --> 00:25:35.740
And when I came here, I remember live in New
York in Manhattan on 50th and 1st Avenue going

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:41.349
to D'Agostino Brothers, typically fancy market,
and asking, "Where are the mushrooms?"

00:25:41.349 --> 00:25:42.710
They say, "Aisle five."

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:44.580
That was canned mushroom.

00:25:44.580 --> 00:25:49.360
You had to go to a specialty store just to
get regular, white button mushroom.

00:25:49.360 --> 00:25:51.179
There was only one salad in supermarket.

00:25:51.179 --> 00:25:53.090
That's what I heard, but nothing else.

00:25:53.090 --> 00:25:57.029
There was no leek, no shallot, no Oriental
vegetable, none of the vegetables.

00:25:57.029 --> 00:25:58.479
It's amazing.

00:25:58.479 --> 00:26:02.440
So certainly, the supermarket have never been
as beautiful as they are now.

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:04.619
It's just amazing.

00:26:04.619 --> 00:26:06.669
And people already saying "no one cook anymore."

00:26:06.669 --> 00:26:07.750
Well, no one cook.

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:09.760
I mean, what do they do with the stuff at
the supermarket?

00:26:09.760 --> 00:26:10.760
[laughter]

00:26:10.760 --> 00:26:13.359
At the end of the week, someone would dump
it.

00:26:13.359 --> 00:26:15.169
Someone must be buying it.

00:26:15.169 --> 00:26:16.629
So, yes.

00:26:16.629 --> 00:26:18.809
It has explode.

00:26:18.809 --> 00:26:24.460
And someone on television the other day was
saying there is 407 television, I mean, cooking

00:26:24.460 --> 00:26:28.740
television show on television, from The Cooking
Channel, to the Food Channel Network, from

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:32.690
Travel, from Oxygen, from PBS, too.

00:26:32.690 --> 00:26:37.519
That at the time when I was doing even the
show with Julia, before it was pre-Food Channel

00:26:37.519 --> 00:26:43.110
Networks, so, except for PBS, there wasn't
that many thing going on in cooking.

00:26:43.110 --> 00:26:45.889
I'm still on PBS.

00:26:45.889 --> 00:26:51.599
And for me, PBS is the best because I don't
have to look out to the sponsor, I do basically

00:26:51.599 --> 00:26:53.119
what I want to.

00:26:53.119 --> 00:26:54.119
It's--.

00:26:54.119 --> 00:26:57.619
And I'm faithful when I'm good somewhere.

00:26:57.619 --> 00:26:58.619
I stay.

00:26:58.619 --> 00:27:00.239
So, that's what I did.

00:27:00.239 --> 00:27:01.629
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Great.

00:27:01.629 --> 00:27:06.799
So, I'm gonna open up questions to our audience
'cause we have a very inquisitive audience,

00:27:06.799 --> 00:27:07.799
I'm sure.

00:27:07.799 --> 00:27:09.559
And I'm sure they wanna ask you lots of questions.

00:27:09.559 --> 00:27:10.559
So.

00:27:10.559 --> 00:27:12.989
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: All right.

00:27:12.989 --> 00:27:14.359
Yes, sir?

00:27:14.359 --> 00:27:20.879
&gt;&gt;male #2: I remember watching your shows
that you did with your daughter.

00:27:20.879 --> 00:27:23.249
And I couldn't help feeling that there was
some frustration on your part with her cooking

00:27:23.249 --> 00:27:24.249
ability.

00:27:24.249 --> 00:27:25.249
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: I'm sorry.

00:27:25.249 --> 00:27:26.249
You know, my--.

00:27:26.249 --> 00:27:27.249
I'm getting old now.

00:27:27.249 --> 00:27:28.249
My hear is--.

00:27:28.249 --> 00:27:29.249
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, he was wondering, he saw
you cooking with your daughter one time.

00:27:29.249 --> 00:27:30.249
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Oh, yeah.

00:27:30.249 --> 00:27:32.299
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: And noticed some frustration
on your face.

00:27:32.299 --> 00:27:33.299
[laughter]

00:27:33.299 --> 00:27:37.029
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Do you have kid?

00:27:37.029 --> 00:27:38.029
[laughter]

00:27:38.029 --> 00:27:39.029
I mean, yeah of course.

00:27:39.029 --> 00:27:40.029
I cook with her--.

00:27:40.029 --> 00:27:41.029
[laughter]

00:27:41.029 --> 00:27:43.989
I cooked with her last week in that series
here.

00:27:43.989 --> 00:27:49.029
I have Claudine cook with me a couple of show
and my granddaughter, Shorey, cook with me,

00:27:49.029 --> 00:27:50.029
too.

00:27:50.029 --> 00:27:51.700
It was really fun.

00:27:51.700 --> 00:27:53.840
When Claudine was small--.

00:27:53.840 --> 00:27:57.580
I mean, I never got baby food, you know?

00:27:57.580 --> 00:27:59.789
Whatever we cooked, I put it in the blender
and gave it to her.

00:27:59.789 --> 00:28:04.520
I mean, I stuffed the seasoning, too, so that
she get used to the taste of pasta with garlic

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:05.590
or whatever.

00:28:05.590 --> 00:28:07.590
It's kind of crazy.

00:28:07.590 --> 00:28:15.749
People, they are going to have pizza for the
kids or buy food and then, once a month everyone

00:28:15.749 --> 00:28:19.410
eat together or they have friend coming for
dinner.

00:28:19.410 --> 00:28:23.690
The do a roasted veal with artichokes and
they send pizza for the kids or whatever.

00:28:23.690 --> 00:28:27.330
And then, the kid get to be ten years old
[clears throat] after his first communion

00:28:27.330 --> 00:28:31.379
or his bar mitzvah or whatever, almost at
once say, "Now, you eat that."

00:28:31.379 --> 00:28:33.520
Kid say, "I won't eat that stuff.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:34.520
What is this?

00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:36.399
I never eat that in my life."

00:28:36.399 --> 00:28:38.529
You cannot treat the kid this way.

00:28:38.529 --> 00:28:40.419
It has to eat exactly what you're eating.

00:28:40.419 --> 00:28:45.279
When Claudine was not even a year old, in
the kitchen, she was I gave her a spoon and

00:28:45.279 --> 00:28:46.279
she stir.

00:28:46.279 --> 00:28:47.279
I say, "Stir it."

00:28:47.279 --> 00:28:48.279
So, she stir the pot.

00:28:48.279 --> 00:28:49.749
So, she stir when she made it.

00:28:49.749 --> 00:28:52.529
And she was going to taste it, of course.

00:28:52.529 --> 00:28:56.869
And then, we always sit down for dinner.

00:28:56.869 --> 00:29:00.690
And it's not like we eat a la carte and everyone
is like, "I want this."

00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:01.690
No.

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:04.979
Claudine comes, three years old, she says,
"Mom, what's for dinner?"

00:29:04.979 --> 00:29:06.509
My wife say, "Food."

00:29:06.509 --> 00:29:07.509
[laughter]

00:29:07.509 --> 00:29:10.169
And she still says that now she's 43.

00:29:10.169 --> 00:29:12.299
So, and with her daughter.

00:29:12.299 --> 00:29:13.299
So, yes.

00:29:13.299 --> 00:29:14.299
It's very important.

00:29:14.299 --> 00:29:19.480
I mean, the kitchen is about the best place
that a child can be in.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:23.159
After school, come there to do your homework.

00:29:23.159 --> 00:29:27.450
The clinking of the noise of the kitchen,
the voice of your mother, the voice of your

00:29:27.450 --> 00:29:31.659
father, those smells, those tastes, that will
stay with you the rest of your life.

00:29:31.659 --> 00:29:34.499
There's something very, very secure in there.

00:29:34.499 --> 00:29:40.720
You look at those kid in Afghanistan, 20,
22 years old in time of danger.

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:42.320
What do you think they think of?

00:29:42.320 --> 00:29:46.869
They think of their mother apple pie or the
clam chowder or whatever it may be because

00:29:46.869 --> 00:29:49.690
those tastes are more than the food itself.

00:29:49.690 --> 00:29:52.609
There is a security to this there with others.

00:29:52.609 --> 00:29:55.570
I think was a Chinese philosopher who say
"What is patriotism?

00:29:55.570 --> 00:29:59.899
It's only the taste of the dishes you had
as a child."

00:29:59.899 --> 00:30:02.450
And there's a great deal of truth in this.

00:30:02.450 --> 00:30:04.070
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Great.

00:30:04.070 --> 00:30:05.149
Thank you.

00:30:05.149 --> 00:30:06.149
Anyone else?

00:30:06.149 --> 00:30:07.149
[pause]

00:30:07.149 --> 00:30:08.149
All right.

00:30:08.149 --> 00:30:09.440
Come on.

00:30:09.440 --> 00:30:11.249
We have a food legend here.

00:30:11.249 --> 00:30:12.249
[laughter]

00:30:12.249 --> 00:30:16.909
&gt;&gt;female #3: Building on top of that question.

00:30:16.909 --> 00:30:19.252
What's your first memory in the kitchen as
a child?

00:30:19.252 --> 00:30:20.809
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: My first memory in the kitchen
as a child, I think I discuss it.

00:30:20.809 --> 00:30:25.049
I have a book called "The Apprentice," which
I did before that guy did that show called

00:30:25.049 --> 00:30:26.509
"The Apprentice."

00:30:26.509 --> 00:30:27.509
[laughter]

00:30:27.509 --> 00:30:29.960
And it's a cook's memoir, you know?

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:35.029
And I left home when I was 13 to go into formal
apprenticeship.

00:30:35.029 --> 00:30:38.429
But when I left home, home was a restaurant
where my mother was a chef.

00:30:38.429 --> 00:30:43.690
So, from age, I don't know, five, six, I was
in the kitchen and my aunt had restaurant.

00:30:43.690 --> 00:30:48.239
What I talk about there [clears throat] an
instance which happened to me during the war

00:30:48.239 --> 00:30:49.239
in France.

00:30:49.239 --> 00:30:50.559
I was, I think, five years old or so.

00:30:50.559 --> 00:30:53.229
And I was sent to a farm for the summer.

00:30:53.229 --> 00:30:55.149
[clears throat] Excuse me.

00:30:55.149 --> 00:30:56.469
We really didn't have much to eat.

00:30:56.469 --> 00:31:00.169
But there, we knew during the vacation we
going to a farm where there is cow.

00:31:00.169 --> 00:31:03.440
And then, there is butter and milk and stuff
like this.

00:31:03.440 --> 00:31:10.179
And I remember my mother taking me there and
leaving me there with the farmer.

00:31:10.179 --> 00:31:19.110
And I went, the farmer took me to the barn
where the woman was milking the cow there.

00:31:19.110 --> 00:31:20.230
And I was sad.

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:22.179
I mean, my mother left.

00:31:22.179 --> 00:31:23.442
I was a little kid.

00:31:23.442 --> 00:31:29.970
So, she gave that glass of milk there--transforming
and still warm from the, right out of the

00:31:29.970 --> 00:31:30.970
teats.

00:31:30.970 --> 00:31:35.659
And that probably one of the first remember
that I--.

00:31:35.659 --> 00:31:38.210
Because especially at that time, that wasn't
that common.

00:31:38.210 --> 00:31:41.739
We really didn't have milk for lunch or something
to drink.

00:31:41.739 --> 00:31:44.409
But that was a powerful memory.

00:31:44.409 --> 00:31:46.269
An old one, too.

00:31:46.269 --> 00:31:47.919
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yes.

00:31:47.919 --> 00:31:51.419
&gt;&gt;female #4: What would you eat for your last
meal?

00:31:51.419 --> 00:31:53.409
I know there would be bread or wine, but what
else would you put--?

00:31:53.409 --> 00:31:54.409
[laughter]

00:31:54.409 --> 00:31:55.409
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Bread and butter.

00:31:55.409 --> 00:31:56.409
Well, we did, yeah.

00:31:56.409 --> 00:31:57.409
See, all of those--.

00:31:57.409 --> 00:32:00.749
I got a book published a couple of years ago,
"My Last Meal."

00:32:00.749 --> 00:32:04.139
There's like 50 chef and I'm part of them.

00:32:04.139 --> 00:32:12.369
If it has to be my last meal, it would have
to be very, very, very, very, very long to

00:32:12.369 --> 00:32:13.369
stop me.

00:32:13.369 --> 00:32:14.369
[laughter]

00:32:14.369 --> 00:32:16.169
So, maybe a year or so.

00:32:16.169 --> 00:32:17.169
[laughter]

00:32:17.169 --> 00:32:24.469
And through that, from a ham sandwich to ham
and egg to hot duck to caviar to Dom Perignon

00:32:24.469 --> 00:32:27.659
to roasted squab to--everything is in there.

00:32:27.659 --> 00:32:28.670
I think that I like to eat.

00:32:28.670 --> 00:32:29.670
[laughter]

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:30.670
Right.

00:32:30.670 --> 00:32:31.670
[pause]

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:32.670
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Anyone else?

00:32:32.670 --> 00:32:33.670
Yes.

00:32:33.670 --> 00:32:34.670
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yes, ma'am.

00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:36.309
&gt;&gt;female #5: With all the new types of tools
that you can use in the kitchen, is there

00:32:36.309 --> 00:32:49.320
certain things that I guess have come out
since when you started cooking till now that

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:54.480
you really think are great to have in the
kitchen that you recommend?

00:32:54.480 --> 00:32:55.480
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: You think about equipment?

00:32:55.480 --> 00:32:56.480
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yeah.

00:32:56.480 --> 00:32:57.480
Like, maybe your favorite hand tool or Peltex.

00:32:57.480 --> 00:32:58.480
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yeah.

00:32:58.480 --> 00:32:59.809
Well, you know you can't beat the rubber spatula.

00:32:59.809 --> 00:33:00.809
[laughter]

00:33:00.809 --> 00:33:03.611
I mean, I was an apprentice pre-rubber spatula.

00:33:03.611 --> 00:33:07.140
Rubber spatula and plastic wrap, right.

00:33:07.140 --> 00:33:08.140
Very good.

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:10.019
We didn't have it.

00:33:10.019 --> 00:33:11.330
A good vegetable peeler.

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:12.330
You need a good knife.

00:33:12.330 --> 00:33:16.100
And a good knife is a sharp one, regardless
of the brand.

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:20.719
You have to be able to have an overripe tomato,
run it on top of it and it cut right through

00:33:20.719 --> 00:33:23.080
it and it's probably a good knife.

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:24.480
A good board, you know?

00:33:24.480 --> 00:33:25.480
Solid.

00:33:25.480 --> 00:33:26.480
A good pot a good knife.

00:33:26.480 --> 00:33:27.700
I mean, very basic equipment.

00:33:27.700 --> 00:33:31.149
Two or three piece and that's all you need,
frankly.

00:33:31.149 --> 00:33:33.740
We have a pot in France, we call a pot like
that.

00:33:33.740 --> 00:33:36.210
And it's called a "l'effet tu."

00:33:36.210 --> 00:33:39.370
L'effet tu meaning do all.

00:33:39.370 --> 00:33:40.549
That the name, l'effet tu.

00:33:40.549 --> 00:33:46.139
And when I was a kid, I don't remember my
mother ever cooking anything else but l'effet

00:33:46.139 --> 00:33:47.139
tu there.

00:33:47.139 --> 00:33:49.850
It's like a wok for the Chinese basically.

00:33:49.850 --> 00:33:51.929
So, yeah.

00:33:51.929 --> 00:33:53.950
You can use and reuse, too.

00:33:53.950 --> 00:33:59.049
I mean, it's great to have type of kitchen
that have equipment and you need three knife.

00:33:59.049 --> 00:34:00.679
I mean, you need a large knife to chop.

00:34:00.679 --> 00:34:03.710
And you need a utility knife and a small one.

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:08.399
That being said, I probably have 300 maybe
at home or more.

00:34:08.399 --> 00:34:09.399
[laughter]

00:34:09.399 --> 00:34:10.399
So, no.

00:34:10.399 --> 00:34:12.010
Good equipment is important.

00:34:12.010 --> 00:34:15.260
And good ingredient is the primary thing.

00:34:15.260 --> 00:34:20.300
If you have good ingredient, good equipment,
the less you screw it up, the better it is.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:26.440
And that what food is all about--going to
the market, getting a few things.

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:33.400
I mean, now we are very big with organic things
and with farmer and all that.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:35.890
But, of course, in this country it's all really
the same.

00:34:35.890 --> 00:34:37.520
You go one way, people get berserk.

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:39.760
I mean, I have been to restaurant.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:43.580
They come and they bring you a carrot that
say, that carrot's name is Evan.

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:45.370
It was born with 700--.

00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:46.370
[laughter]

00:34:46.370 --> 00:34:47.620
Give me a break.

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:48.620
Give me the carrot.

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:53.220
I mean, it can go too far the other way, too.

00:34:53.220 --> 00:34:54.740
But it's certainly good.

00:34:54.740 --> 00:34:57.650
I mean, my mother, my father, were both organic
farmer.

00:34:57.650 --> 00:35:00.660
Of course, the word "organic" did not exist.

00:35:00.660 --> 00:35:04.890
But the chemical fertilizer did not exist,
either.

00:35:04.890 --> 00:35:09.890
And fungicide, insecticide, pesticide did
not exist either for everyone with an organic

00:35:09.890 --> 00:35:10.890
farmer.

00:35:10.890 --> 00:35:16.320
You want, get some cow or horse manure or
chicken manure and place and you do the gardens.

00:35:16.320 --> 00:35:19.550
So, it's not that we don't know how to do
it going back to this.

00:35:19.550 --> 00:35:23.520
So, and that what's going on now.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:25.430
So, going back to your question.

00:35:25.430 --> 00:35:27.880
The food has been exploding here.

00:35:27.880 --> 00:35:29.450
A revolution in the last 30 years.

00:35:29.450 --> 00:35:32.340
It should be totally amazing.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:33.540
And I know I've been part of it.

00:35:33.540 --> 00:35:36.810
And it seem to be going on and on, so that's
great.

00:35:36.810 --> 00:35:39.990
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, let me just ask you a
real quick question.

00:35:39.990 --> 00:35:41.530
What do you think of sous vide?

00:35:41.530 --> 00:35:43.170
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Sous vide is good.

00:35:43.170 --> 00:35:45.750
With sous vide, that's what I use at Howard
Johnson in 1960.

00:35:45.750 --> 00:35:49.180
It was called cryovacs at that time.

00:35:49.180 --> 00:35:50.460
It was sous vide.

00:35:50.460 --> 00:35:53.980
We used to cook the thing this way at low
temperature and so forth.

00:35:53.980 --> 00:35:55.260
But if you're talking about--.

00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:58.590
Yeah, there is a great deal of things you
can use with that.

00:35:58.590 --> 00:35:59.590
Terrific.

00:35:59.590 --> 00:36:04.890
And but you may be talking about molecular
cuisine or stuff like that, too, more advanced

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:06.400
like Ferran Adria.

00:36:06.400 --> 00:36:09.180
I was with Ferran Adria on actually three
weeks ago.

00:36:09.180 --> 00:36:11.720
I went at the Food and Wine Festival in Cancun.

00:36:11.720 --> 00:36:14.420
It was the first time they did it.

00:36:14.420 --> 00:36:17.320
And Ferran came--some other Spanish chef,
too.

00:36:17.320 --> 00:36:20.160
And it is an amazing thing.

00:36:20.160 --> 00:36:22.140
I mean, what they do.

00:36:22.140 --> 00:36:23.430
It can be tiring, too.

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:29.860
I mean, basically it seems especially done
by someone else with not as talented as those

00:36:29.860 --> 00:36:31.160
chef are.

00:36:31.160 --> 00:36:35.600
And too badly it end up being, the whole idea
is to stump you with "Wow.

00:36:35.600 --> 00:36:36.600
What is that?"

00:36:36.600 --> 00:36:38.400
And you bite and it's liquid inside.

00:36:38.400 --> 00:36:39.400
"Whoa."

00:36:39.400 --> 00:36:41.850
But after a while, it get tiring.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:47.210
But, or then they give you an ice cream cone.

00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:50.160
And you bite it and it's mashed turnips or
whatever.

00:36:50.160 --> 00:36:53.190
So, your brain is already working throughout
that taste.

00:36:53.190 --> 00:36:54.850
It cuts you in half.

00:36:54.850 --> 00:36:56.410
And this is--.

00:36:56.410 --> 00:37:01.920
I had that in China 25 years ago, eating with
the monk, which were eating--.

00:37:01.920 --> 00:37:02.920
I had duck.

00:37:02.920 --> 00:37:03.920
I had chicken.

00:37:03.920 --> 00:37:09.750
I had all of this and it was all soybeans,
done, set in type of cuisine.

00:37:09.750 --> 00:37:12.990
And that was amazing, that type of cuisine.

00:37:12.990 --> 00:37:20.310
But you are actually in town here, Jean Paul
Gaultier, which is a French designer, very

00:37:20.310 --> 00:37:24.770
extreme doing stuff like, I don't know, Madonna
or Lady Gaga or whatever.

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:27.500
I mean, the weirdest stuff.

00:37:27.500 --> 00:37:33.520
So, you see the model working down the walkway
wearing those enormous, you say, "Oh my God.

00:37:33.520 --> 00:37:36.300
Who's going to wear that stuff?"

00:37:36.300 --> 00:37:41.360
And yes, about five or ten years later, it
trickles down to the pret-a-porter, to a certain

00:37:41.360 --> 00:37:42.360
extent.

00:37:42.360 --> 00:37:47.090
So, in a sense, the cuisine of Ferran Adria,
that type of extreme, now you get that.

00:37:47.090 --> 00:37:49.160
Then, it down trickle down eventually.

00:37:49.160 --> 00:37:51.020
Do just like nouvelle cuisine did.

00:37:51.020 --> 00:37:57.800
Before I came to, when I was in France, work
at the Plaza Athenee in Paris, Maxim, Fouquet,

00:37:57.800 --> 00:37:59.020
great restaurant.

00:37:59.020 --> 00:38:01.950
We would never, never have served something
on a plate.

00:38:01.950 --> 00:38:06.610
Even more so, my mother with that small restaurant,
my aunt, they all have full restaurant, for

00:38:06.610 --> 00:38:07.610
worker.

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:11.020
I mean, very inexpensive type of restaurant.

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:14.000
Nothing was ever, ever, ever on a plate.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:17.710
You just bring, if you have a little piece
of fish, you bring it on a platter, too.

00:38:17.710 --> 00:38:22.230
Even at home, my mother, she would do a roast
whatever, put it in the center of the table.

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:23.500
Then, we had bowl salad.

00:38:23.500 --> 00:38:25.690
But never, never set on a plate.

00:38:25.690 --> 00:38:29.020
Nouvelle cuisine came in the '70s, over-sized
plates.

00:38:29.020 --> 00:38:30.620
Chefs started arranging stuff, too.

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:34.360
And now, you don't have a chef who would serve
anything else, but serving something on a

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:35.410
plate.

00:38:35.410 --> 00:38:41.480
So, that's a legacy of nouvelle cuisine as
well as cooking vegetable different way--other

00:38:41.480 --> 00:38:42.970
type of things, of course.

00:38:42.970 --> 00:38:44.940
So, it trickled down eventually.

00:38:44.940 --> 00:38:48.170
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Great answer.

00:38:48.170 --> 00:38:49.560
Yes.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:58.715
&gt;&gt;male #6: So, what do you think about the
future of French cuisine and also French culinary

00:38:58.715 --> 00:38:59.715
instruction?

00:38:59.715 --> 00:39:00.715
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Ah-hah.

00:39:00.715 --> 00:39:01.715
&gt;&gt;male #6: [inaudible]

00:39:01.715 --> 00:39:02.715
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yeah, that's a good point.

00:39:02.715 --> 00:39:03.715
It's quite different.

00:39:03.715 --> 00:39:04.715
Yet, however, you go to France, people are
really not too aware of this.

00:39:04.715 --> 00:39:06.870
You still have a lot of very good restaurant.

00:39:06.870 --> 00:39:13.500
Unfortunately for most American, they look
at French cooking in the context of star restaurant.

00:39:13.500 --> 00:39:19.850
You do have to two star and one, three star
here in the California, which is amazing.

00:39:19.850 --> 00:39:21.440
And in New York, we have more.

00:39:21.440 --> 00:39:25.940
I mean, there is only 21, I think, 21 three-star
restaurant in France.

00:39:25.940 --> 00:39:32.950
There's about 80 or so two-star and maybe
400 one-star, with 500, 600 in the whole star

00:39:32.950 --> 00:39:33.950
system.

00:39:33.950 --> 00:39:38.440
But there is 146 stars in restaurants in France,
I believe.

00:39:38.440 --> 00:39:44.830
But Americans, they are from--especially years
ago--would go to France and eat like in three

00:39:44.830 --> 00:39:47.580
four-, three-star restaurant in a week.

00:39:47.580 --> 00:39:51.620
Of course, it's an overload of truffle and
reduction of cream and stuff like this.

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:53.820
That's what that type of restaurant is.

00:39:53.820 --> 00:39:59.570
But when I was taking group with BU, Boston
University, we go maybe to one one-star, sometime

00:39:59.570 --> 00:40:02.240
one two-star, but other than that, I take
them to brasserie, bistro, too.

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:03.440
And they say, "Wow.

00:40:03.440 --> 00:40:04.610
This is French cooking?"

00:40:04.610 --> 00:40:10.210
I say, "This was more Italian like a roast
with the juice, or a puree of potato or whatever."

00:40:10.210 --> 00:40:12.630
Which is basically what people eat.

00:40:12.630 --> 00:40:16.910
I mean, I'll go on the road when I'm in France
and I go to like, La Ferme in Auberge, the

00:40:16.910 --> 00:40:17.910
farm in.

00:40:17.910 --> 00:40:20.900
There is a little book for that.

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:25.800
And more than 60 percent of what you eat there
has to be produced by that farm.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:27.360
Sometimes, it's 80, 90 percent.

00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:29.120
I've been to some farm.

00:40:29.120 --> 00:40:36.020
I remember one time I was in the Gerar area,
the Northeast part of France near Alsace,

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:38.230
with my wife and another couple.

00:40:38.230 --> 00:40:42.190
And I saw a sign Ferme Auberge, a piece of
wood on the road.

00:40:42.190 --> 00:40:43.190
We follow that small road.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:46.290
Then, at the corner of the road, I saw a house
there.

00:40:46.290 --> 00:40:48.640
It was, I said, "It's probably in there."

00:40:48.640 --> 00:40:52.410
So, I saw some chicken coming out, a pig in
the courtyard.

00:40:52.410 --> 00:40:54.850
I go in and there was a little girl doing
her homework at the table.

00:40:54.850 --> 00:40:56.830
I say, "Is that the farm Auberge?"

00:40:56.830 --> 00:40:57.830
She said, "Yes."

00:40:57.830 --> 00:40:58.830
I say, "You think we can eat?"

00:40:58.830 --> 00:40:59.990
She said, "Just call my mom."

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:04.250
So, she called her mom who came with her apron
and then her father came.

00:41:04.250 --> 00:41:05.650
There was no one.

00:41:05.650 --> 00:41:06.650
And her father say, "OK.

00:41:06.650 --> 00:41:07.790
I'm gonna go shave."

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:08.960
I say, "You don't have to shave."

00:41:08.960 --> 00:41:10.660
He say, "I'll go pick up wild mushroom."

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:11.740
I said, "Better idea."

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:12.740
[laughter]

00:41:12.740 --> 00:41:14.160
And so, he went to pick up mushroom.

00:41:14.160 --> 00:41:17.910
She cooked whatever they cooked that day,
probably cost her six or eight dollars per

00:41:17.910 --> 00:41:18.910
person.

00:41:18.910 --> 00:41:21.410
And this is the type of food that I like to
eat more.

00:41:21.410 --> 00:41:27.920
Granted occasionally, I'll eat at PER SE and
all those great restaurant, but this is naturally

00:41:27.920 --> 00:41:30.210
what food memory are made of.

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:31.210
It's not visceral enough.

00:41:31.210 --> 00:41:32.210
[pause]

00:41:32.210 --> 00:41:33.210
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Anyone else?

00:41:33.210 --> 00:41:34.210
[pause]

00:41:34.210 --> 00:41:35.210
Yes.

00:41:35.210 --> 00:41:36.210
&gt;&gt;female #7: So, I love to cook, but there's
one thing I still hate doing.

00:41:36.210 --> 00:41:37.210
I've done much more challenging things, but
I can't stand chopping cilantro.

00:41:37.210 --> 00:41:38.210
It sticks to my hands.

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:50.760
And I was just wondering if you have any weird
little things like that, that you just hate

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:51.760
doing.

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:52.830
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: To clean up your hand?

00:41:52.830 --> 00:41:54.700
&gt;&gt;female #7: No, no.

00:41:54.700 --> 00:41:58.890
Just like, chopping onions or chopping cilantro
or whatever.

00:41:58.890 --> 00:41:59.946
I'm sure you do much more challenging things,
but--.

00:41:59.946 --> 00:42:00.946
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yeah.

00:42:00.946 --> 00:42:01.946
Well, you have to look at that tape there.

00:42:01.946 --> 00:42:03.320
I mean, all of the technique is in there.

00:42:03.320 --> 00:42:09.500
And all of those technique from, yeah, from
cilantro whatever.

00:42:09.500 --> 00:42:14.480
I mean, I'm always washing my hand, washing
the sheer part of my board.

00:42:14.480 --> 00:42:18.090
It's almost a conditioned reflex for me.

00:42:18.090 --> 00:42:21.330
But when I finish that, my wife come behind
and rewash it anyway.

00:42:21.330 --> 00:42:22.330
[laughter]

00:42:22.330 --> 00:42:27.470
&gt;&gt;male #8: So, is there anything that you
don't like to cook?

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:28.820
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Not really.

00:42:28.820 --> 00:42:37.620
I'm not crazy about coconut or marshmallow,
but otherwise I think I eat any kind of cuisine

00:42:37.620 --> 00:42:38.690
from other areas.

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:40.120
Some stuff I like better than others, but
not really.

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:41.120
[pause]

00:42:41.120 --> 00:42:42.120
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Yes.

00:42:42.120 --> 00:42:43.120
&gt;&gt;female #9: The same thing.

00:42:43.120 --> 00:42:54.220
Do you have any pet peeves when you dine out
in restaurants?

00:42:54.220 --> 00:42:56.884
Do you have anything that really gets to you?

00:42:56.884 --> 00:42:57.884
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Dining out around here?

00:42:57.884 --> 00:42:58.884
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Or anywhere.

00:42:58.884 --> 00:42:59.884
&gt;&gt;female #9: Anywhere.

00:42:59.884 --> 00:43:00.884
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Anywhere?

00:43:00.884 --> 00:43:01.884
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Any place you went to dine
out.

00:43:01.884 --> 00:43:02.884
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Yeah, it's always great.

00:43:02.884 --> 00:43:03.884
I mean, as I said, where they know you the
best.

00:43:03.884 --> 00:43:07.870
I mean, I know some small little restaurant
where I am.

00:43:07.870 --> 00:43:13.450
And for me, very often, instead of working,
I talk to a young chef and instead of doing

00:43:13.450 --> 00:43:19.000
something extraordinary that no one has seen,
I'm often being the devil's advocate, like

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:20.000
at BU.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:21.330
They say, "Well, what are we going to do today?"

00:43:21.330 --> 00:43:25.800
I say, "Well, today, let's do a lobster roll
and a BLT and a hot dog."

00:43:25.800 --> 00:43:27.250
"What are we missing?

00:43:27.250 --> 00:43:28.830
You crazy or what?"

00:43:28.830 --> 00:43:29.830
No.

00:43:29.830 --> 00:43:33.800
The idea there is yes, you can always do a
better hot dog.

00:43:33.800 --> 00:43:38.421
You can always find a better hot dog with
a better mustard, with a better bread, with

00:43:38.421 --> 00:43:42.570
a better way of grating it, with a better
way, so that, or like a lobster roll, like

00:43:42.570 --> 00:43:47.900
my friend Jean-Claude, with my oldest friend
that I stay working with me for de Gaulle.

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:53.430
And he come to Connecticut and he said, "Let's
go have a lobster roll at The Shack on the

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:54.430
Boston north border."

00:43:54.430 --> 00:43:56.710
The Shack is there in summer, closed in winter.

00:43:56.710 --> 00:44:00.600
Well, the guy buy the Philadelphia roll that
we used to have at Howard Johnson, a flat

00:44:00.600 --> 00:44:02.340
roll sticking against one another.

00:44:02.340 --> 00:44:04.480
He brown them nicely--butter on each side.

00:44:04.480 --> 00:44:06.910
He has fresh lobster cooked.

00:44:06.910 --> 00:44:09.420
Cracked pepper, salt on top, butter.

00:44:09.420 --> 00:44:11.000
Put that, that's it.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.840
Well, my friend, the professional chef, will
remember.

00:44:13.840 --> 00:44:16.140
He say, "Let's go have a lobster roll there."

00:44:16.140 --> 00:44:17.140
And you do that.

00:44:17.140 --> 00:44:18.200
Let's go have a roast chicken.

00:44:18.200 --> 00:44:21.030
And those guys do hot dog or even hamburger
incredible.

00:44:21.030 --> 00:44:22.940
That's what you remember.

00:44:22.940 --> 00:44:28.850
So, for a young chef, often I say, "Work in
depth rather than wanting to create and you

00:44:28.850 --> 00:44:33.600
end up with a slice of Roquefort on top of
a bowl of raspberry ice cream."

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:34.600
Wow.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:35.600
[laughter]

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:37.110
No one has ever thought of it before.

00:44:37.110 --> 00:44:41.240
Probably reason why no one has thought of
it before.

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:42.240
[laughter]

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:53.230
So, and often unfortunately, it's too much,
the question of if you want of the novelty,

00:44:53.230 --> 00:44:54.880
the--.

00:44:54.880 --> 00:44:56.540
It's not necessarily good.

00:44:56.540 --> 00:45:01.530
I'm very comfortable with thousand and thousand
of dishes that I've had through my life.

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:04.250
I don't need to create stuff.

00:45:04.250 --> 00:45:06.770
And often, what's new for you is very different.

00:45:06.770 --> 00:45:13.470
Tomorrow, you fly into Dakar and you are in
West Africa and you going to have a ceebu

00:45:13.470 --> 00:45:14.470
jen.

00:45:14.470 --> 00:45:15.470
You say, "Wow.

00:45:15.470 --> 00:45:16.470
I never had ceebu jen."

00:45:16.470 --> 00:45:19.740
Well, it's the broken rice that they cook
there with the fish and some hot sauce and

00:45:19.740 --> 00:45:21.280
you hold that in your hand.

00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:22.680
Well, yes.

00:45:22.680 --> 00:45:25.350
So, it can do the rage for two weeks.

00:45:25.350 --> 00:45:29.080
I mean, from one chef to the other, they get
berserk because it's new.

00:45:29.080 --> 00:45:30.080
Fine.

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:31.080
There, what they eat every day.

00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:32.880
This is their national dish, you know?

00:45:32.880 --> 00:45:36.830
If you go around the world like that, that's
basically the way it works.

00:45:36.830 --> 00:45:44.820
&gt;&gt;male #10: So, is there any common mistakes
that chefs will make that you'll notice or

00:45:44.820 --> 00:45:45.820
hear?

00:45:45.820 --> 00:45:46.820
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Oh, yes.

00:45:46.820 --> 00:45:47.820
Yeah.

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:48.820
There is mistake often.

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:52.700
And I say working too much with the, doing
too much with the ingredient.

00:45:52.700 --> 00:45:53.700
That's normal.

00:45:53.700 --> 00:45:56.320
I probably did that when I was in my 20s,
30s.

00:45:56.320 --> 00:46:00.430
Also, you have a plate and add more and they
put a bit of cilantro and they put a bit of

00:46:00.430 --> 00:46:02.510
tarragon, which conflicts with it.

00:46:02.510 --> 00:46:06.410
And you have that type of carrot and you have
olive oil and you have a bit of sesame oil

00:46:06.410 --> 00:46:07.410
and stuff.

00:46:07.410 --> 00:46:08.410
And geez.

00:46:08.410 --> 00:46:09.410
You know.

00:46:09.410 --> 00:46:12.160
So, you sit down.

00:46:12.160 --> 00:46:17.530
And that has happened to be because being
a chef, I go to some food writer conference,

00:46:17.530 --> 00:46:19.210
also because I write about food.

00:46:19.210 --> 00:46:23.340
And so, because I'm a chef, they ask me where
those thing.

00:46:23.340 --> 00:46:29.340
And everything is sliced beautiful, five vegetable
and so they ask people, "What is that?

00:46:29.340 --> 00:46:30.340
Is it good?"

00:46:30.340 --> 00:46:31.340
So, I taste it.

00:46:31.340 --> 00:46:32.340
"Yeah, it's very good.

00:46:32.340 --> 00:46:33.340
What is it?"

00:46:33.340 --> 00:46:34.340
"No idea."

00:46:34.340 --> 00:46:35.550
People don't have any idea.

00:46:35.550 --> 00:46:37.970
It's either a breast of chicken or a breast
of turkey.

00:46:37.970 --> 00:46:39.020
It's white.

00:46:39.020 --> 00:46:40.480
It's standard.

00:46:40.480 --> 00:46:41.940
It's clean.

00:46:41.940 --> 00:46:42.940
And that's what I would tell a chef.

00:46:42.940 --> 00:46:45.240
I say, "I'll put something on your eyes.

00:46:45.240 --> 00:46:46.240
Sit down.

00:46:46.240 --> 00:46:47.240
I'll give you a plate.

00:46:47.240 --> 00:46:50.570
If you tell me, 'That's chicken, there is
mushroom in it and maybe some wine.

00:46:50.570 --> 00:46:51.660
I think there's a bit of white wine.'

00:46:51.660 --> 00:46:53.470
Then, you're probably far enough in the dish.

00:46:53.470 --> 00:46:57.330
The dish is pretty linear and it's pretty
straight-forward and you know what you're

00:46:57.330 --> 00:46:58.450
eating."

00:46:58.450 --> 00:47:02.460
And that basically what you want, to recognize
the food.

00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:07.970
And as you're older like me, after adding
to the plate, you start taking away, taking

00:47:07.970 --> 00:47:12.410
away, taking away so that you're left with
one tomato at the right temperature with the

00:47:12.410 --> 00:47:13.410
vestibule, too.

00:47:13.410 --> 00:47:14.410
That's it.

00:47:14.410 --> 00:47:15.410
And I throw shallot on top, whatever.

00:47:15.410 --> 00:47:16.410
That's how it works, usually.

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:17.410
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: Great.

00:47:17.410 --> 00:47:18.410
Anyone else?

00:47:18.410 --> 00:47:19.410
OK.

00:47:19.410 --> 00:47:20.410
Last question 'cause I'm--.

00:47:20.410 --> 00:47:21.410
&gt;&gt;male #11: Do you think you're at your tier
in the process of learning about how to cook?

00:47:21.410 --> 00:47:30.220
Is there anything that stands out to you as
something that you would've changed in which

00:47:30.220 --> 00:47:35.860
you'd avoid a lot of hassle?

00:47:35.860 --> 00:47:39.290
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Anything that stand out for
me for what?

00:47:39.290 --> 00:47:43.210
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: So, during your career, is
there anything that you could change along

00:47:43.210 --> 00:47:44.330
your career?

00:47:44.330 --> 00:47:47.400
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Could change?

00:47:47.400 --> 00:47:48.400
I don't know.

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:50.020
It's a good question.

00:47:50.020 --> 00:47:52.050
The point is that I never had a plan.

00:47:52.050 --> 00:47:56.560
I'm gonna do this and then do this and then,
no.

00:47:56.560 --> 00:47:57.860
Things take over.

00:47:57.860 --> 00:48:04.041
I worked in Paris and I probably work over
a hundred restaurant in Paris because I work

00:48:04.041 --> 00:48:06.350
like, seven years at the Plaza Athenee, too.

00:48:06.350 --> 00:48:10.270
But my day off, I used to work in a large
organization in Paris called La Associate

00:48:10.270 --> 00:48:13.320
de Cuisine in Paris, the Society of the Chef
of Paris.

00:48:13.320 --> 00:48:17.020
And which we should really have in town like
here or New York, where you can go in the

00:48:17.020 --> 00:48:18.020
morning.

00:48:18.020 --> 00:48:19.020
You get a job for the day.

00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:20.730
People call to say, "I need associate today."

00:48:20.730 --> 00:48:22.430
Or, "I need this, that, too."

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:27.010
Great, great training for me because as you
get there, no matter you work in a restaurant,

00:48:27.010 --> 00:48:28.700
it takes you two day to get used to.

00:48:28.700 --> 00:48:29.750
There, it doesn't test.

00:48:29.750 --> 00:48:32.400
After 15, 20 minutes, you have to be cooking.

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:33.450
You're there for the day.

00:48:33.450 --> 00:48:36.250
The chefs say, "Go to that department or that
department."

00:48:36.250 --> 00:48:37.250
You go there.

00:48:37.250 --> 00:48:38.250
What's on the menu today?

00:48:38.250 --> 00:48:39.250
You look.

00:48:39.250 --> 00:48:40.250
You say, "OK."

00:48:40.250 --> 00:48:41.250
Start gathering your ingredient.

00:48:41.250 --> 00:48:42.250
You start working.

00:48:42.250 --> 00:48:43.790
Well, that's very, very good training.

00:48:43.790 --> 00:48:48.460
And I would advise young chefs to do that,
but basically, you work and you meet friend

00:48:48.460 --> 00:48:51.090
and then you have enough work to do something
else.

00:48:51.090 --> 00:48:55.580
I went at the Plaza Athenee in Paris, at that
time the pastry chef was an old man, about

00:48:55.580 --> 00:48:57.340
my age now.

00:48:57.340 --> 00:49:00.780
And he told me, "I work in Chicago when I
was a young man.

00:49:00.780 --> 00:49:03.600
You should go to America and so forth and
that."

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:08.440
And he said, "Well, I have friend and they
can call you to sponsor you if you want."

00:49:08.440 --> 00:49:11.240
So, I had a sponsor in New York.

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:15.400
Yeah, in New York, a French restaurant from
Alsace.

00:49:15.400 --> 00:49:16.720
He sponsors me.

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:23.900
And at that time, the quota and the rule to
come to another country, you come to America

00:49:23.900 --> 00:49:25.430
have changed a great deal now.

00:49:25.430 --> 00:49:29.190
But at that time, each country had their own
quota.

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:32.150
And in France, people really never immigrated
that much.

00:49:32.150 --> 00:49:37.010
So, two months I had a green card and a visa
that I could come.

00:49:37.010 --> 00:49:38.010
In two month.

00:49:38.010 --> 00:49:44.430
But in Italy next door, I think it's about
close to a third of the population immigrated

00:49:44.430 --> 00:49:46.940
from Italy in the 10, 20s, and 30s.

00:49:46.940 --> 00:49:50.560
So, cousin coming, they had to wait like five
years, six years.

00:49:50.560 --> 00:49:54.110
And now, they changed those thing into something
for all Europe now.

00:49:54.110 --> 00:49:56.150
So, it was very good for me to come.

00:49:56.150 --> 00:49:59.240
I came on a student boat, actually.

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:03.170
Student who were coming back from Europe.

00:50:03.170 --> 00:50:06.720
And I saw two aurora borealis and I finish
in Quebec.

00:50:06.720 --> 00:50:09.220
Quebec, I took the train to go to Montreal.

00:50:09.220 --> 00:50:10.560
And Montreal, the train to New York.

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:13.630
And I'm there in Grand Central with my suitcase.

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:15.090
That was it.

00:50:15.090 --> 00:50:19.570
No, those were very good experience.

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:25.920
Even when I left from Lyon, I was 17 years
old and I went to Paris.

00:50:25.920 --> 00:50:27.250
I had work already in Lyon.

00:50:27.250 --> 00:50:28.250
Did my apprenticeship.

00:50:28.250 --> 00:50:29.840
I started at 13.

00:50:29.840 --> 00:50:33.130
I told my mother, "No, I have a job in Paris.

00:50:33.130 --> 00:50:34.130
I have a friend."

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:35.580
I didn't have a job in Paris.

00:50:35.580 --> 00:50:36.580
I didn't have--.

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:37.580
I never been to Paris.

00:50:37.580 --> 00:50:41.150
I arrived there with my suitcase, too, there.

00:50:41.150 --> 00:50:45.040
So, those are good experience to form someone.

00:50:45.040 --> 00:50:46.040
Yeah.

00:50:46.040 --> 00:50:47.240
&gt;&gt;Jeff Freburg: All right.

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:48.240
Well, thank you very much.

00:50:48.240 --> 00:50:49.240
It was a real pleasure.

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:50.240
&gt;&gt;Jacques Pepin: Thank you.

